<p class="head">June, year 1806</p>
<p class="positiveIndent">M<sup>r</sup> Rocheblave being on the eve of taking this departure for Fort William, it was incumbent on him by terms agreed upon, to send people to the Missurie to draw Debts he had made the preceding winter to a free-man who was to trade the indebted goods to <span class="AddHand-author">or with</span> the Pawnees, &amp; who promised to bring their value in furs from thence to the Gros Ventre Village, &amp; there to be delivered to the person acting for NW.C<sup>o</sup> who had the first right to the surplus of the furs (after the debt being paid) at the Missurie Price<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  At the time M<sup>r</sup> Rocheblave had made this debt he was little aware of the danger of sending men to the Missurie; who when there thought themselves at liberty to act according to their fancy &#8211; especially those who had very little to loose by dersertion but their Character<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  After experien<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>cing<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span> the desertion of those who accompanied me last wint<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>er<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span> &amp; knowing how ready others were to follow their example, M<sup>r</sup> Rocheblave was l<span class="AddHand-author">oa</span>th to hasard any more of them<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  After informing me of his embarassments, he asked me if I could possibly undertake the voyage with only M<sup>r</sup> Caldwell<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  I did not hesitate to tell him that there was some danger to travel at that season with horses &amp; proper<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>ty<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span> &amp; with so few people to accompany them; but notwithsan<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>d<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>ing that I would make a triel of it &amp; avoid all danger if possible<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  Therefore every thing being <span class="AddHand-author">got</span> ready we departe<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>d<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span> on the 4<sup>th</sup> of June<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  Myself &amp; M<sup>r</sup> Caldwell had six of the Company's horses, to bring back the intended furs, &amp; some articles for trade, &amp; to purchase horses in case of want<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  A free man who had taken Debts at the H.B. had joined us, &amp; <span class="AddHand-author">we</span> all three continued our march by long &amp; crooked roads to avoid falling on some Indians whether friends or enemies, for in fact all were our enemies for carrying goods to the Missurie &#8211; &amp; tho' we had seen some vestiges we ha<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>d<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span> <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span> good luck to arrive on the bank of the Missurie <span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>with<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>out seeing an Indian<span class="AddHand-editors"><font face="Symbol" size="-3">[</font>.<font face="Symbol" size="-3">]</font></span>  Although <span class="DelHand-author"><span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span></span> <span class="AddHand-author">the</span> face of <span class="Gap">[&#8230;]</span></p>

